id="post-4452" class="post-4452 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-energy tag-australia tag-economy tag-solar"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/07/14/solar-has-won/" title="Permalink to Solar Has Won" rel="bookmark">Solar Has Won</a></h2><div
class="entry-meta"> <span
class="entry-date" title="2014/07/14 1:46 pm"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/07/14/solar-has-won/" title="Solar Has Won" rel="bookmark">2014/07/14 1:46 pm</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="comments-link"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/2014/07/14/solar-has-won/#comments">Leave a Comment</a></span><span
class="entry-meta-sep"> / </span><span
class="entry-author author vcard"><a
href="http://www.thingsaregood.com/author/administrator/" title="by Adam Clare" rel="author">Adam Clare</a></span></div><div
class="entry-content clearfix"><p><a
href="http://i0.wp.com/www.thingsaregood.com/wp-content/uploads/2007/01/sdfsdure-2.png"><img
src="http://i0.wp.com/www.thingsaregood.com/wp-content/uploads/2007/01/sdfsdure-2.png?resize=156%2C187" alt="sdfsdure-2.png" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-934" data-recalc-dims="1" /></a></p><p>In Australia the amount of energy being produced by sustainable systems caused the price to fall so low it went in to the negative. This will not be the last time we see this. As more places adopt renewable energy into their power grids the old models of industry will be forced to change &#8211; meaning a better world for consumers, producers, and the environment!</p><blockquote><p>Last week, for the first time in memory, the wholesale price of electricity in Queensland fell into negative territory – in the middle of the day.</p><p>For several days the price, normally around $40-$50 a megawatt hour, hovered in and around zero. Prices were deflated throughout the week, largely because of the influence of one of the newest, biggest power stations in the state – rooftop solar.</p><p>“Negative pricing” moves, as they are known, are not uncommon. But they are only supposed to happen at night, when most of the population is mostly asleep, demand is down, and operators of coal fired generators are reluctant to switch off. So they pay others to pick up their output.</p></blockquote><p><a
href="http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/jul/07/solar-has-won-even-if-coal-were-free-to-burn-power-stations-couldnt-compete?CMP=fb_gu">Read more.</a></p><div
class="sharedaddy sd-sharing-enabled"><div
